		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4103343)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4103343">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/darkstuff" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1581620); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1581620&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252432" alt="DarkStuff" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1581620)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/darkstuff" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1581620); return false;" >DarkStuff</a></span> <span class="odate time_1546187177 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Dec 2018 16:26</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4103343">
									

<p>Ack, I'm sorry. I kept forgetting to comment on this. But, let's get the obvious out of the way:</p>
<p><em>Hot damn, that's one spicy story.</em></p>
<p>At first, I was a little unhappy that people seem to be making up departments every time they write for Wonder World!™, but I've warmed up to it. In fact, I'm now in support of it. I think it is fun to <em>think</em> you know how big Wondertainment is, and then be wrong time and time again. I mean, they're a successful <em>multiversal</em> company. They must be <strong>enormous</strong>. And with that in mind, I am beginning to really enjoy having Wondertainment continuously take people (myself included) by surprise in regards to its size.</p>
<p>Also, I'm glad to see that the weather being entirely artificial as well is addressed. Good good. Well, alright, in this case, <em>not</em> entirely artificial (or maybe someone sabotaged it, so maybe it still is), but they have a system to control the weather and I like that.</p>
<p>I also am in support of the idea that if you work in Wondertainment, you have to meet their &quot;happiness standard&quot; for the workplace. Though that does make me wonder how 3T gets by&#8230; good job!</p>

							</div>

								
					
